The site was [[archaeological excavation|excavated]] in 1970 and again in 1976, during which time the [[:en:Burial chamber|Burial chamber]] was uncovered and found to be a peculiar two-tied structure with length of 2.2 meters and width of 0.8 meters. The interior of the [[sarcophagus]] was painted in [[vermillion]], and contained the remains of two adult men and women along with many [[:en:Burial goods|Burial goods]]. These included an almost intact set of armor made from iron plates, iron weapons and swords, agricultural implements, three [[:en:Bronze mirror|Bronze mirror]]s, beads and jewelry. One of the bronze mirrors, or ''[[Shinju-kyo]]'' was of especial interest, as it was identical to mirrors found at the Uchikoshi Kofun in [[:en:Gifu|Gifu]] and the [[Teradani Chōshizuka Kofun]] in [[:en:Iwata, Shizuoka|Iwata, Shizuoka]]. Many of the excavated artifacts are now preserved at the [[Tokyo National Museum]].
